Tutorial 1 - What is Hono?

7 steps

In this tutorial, you will learn about Hono and compare some similarities and differences from other middleware frameworks such as Express and Oak.

During the tutorial, you will also prepare a project setup that you will use throughout the campaign. Therefore, this tutorial is a prerequisite for the subsequent quests.

The project setup will consist of a preparation of project structure, creating some example routes, and adding a Deno task. This will also allow us to experiment with some routes to be used throughout this campaign.

Let's dive in and learn about Hono 🔥

Prerequisites

  • Recommended to have finished the Soar with Deno from Learn.
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript.
  • A working development environment of VSCode.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the 🆘 | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have finished the Soar with Deno from Learn.
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript.
  • A working development environment of VSCode.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Explain why Hono is fast.
  • Apply standard Web APIs with Hono.
  • Build simpler backend code with Hono.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 7

  • Step 1: Installing Deno

    ℹ️ For the sake of uniformity in this campaign, we require users to use a Unix-like operating system like MacOS or Linux. Windows users can use GitHub Codespaces to have a Linux environment.

    Preparing Your GitHub Codespaces

    This section is exclusively for those users who want to use a cloud environment, specifically, GitHub Codespaces.

    If you are already familiar with how to use other cloud environments or are currently using WSL or MacOS, you are free to skip this section to head over to the Installing Deno section.

    This campaign will only cover instructions for GitHub Codespaces and not other cloud environment providers. Head to the documentation to learn more about GitHub Codespaces.

    Creating A GitHub Account

    If you already have a GitHub Account, feel free to move over to the next section of this step.

    GitHub Codespaces require a GitHub Account. If you have not created a GitHub Account, sign up here. Once you have your GitHub Account, you can start creating a new repository.

    Creating A New Repository

    To create a new repository, log in to your GitHub dashboard at https://github.com using your GitHub Account credentials.

    Look towards the upper right corner of the page. You should see a plus button with a down triangle. Click the plus button and it should drop down a list of options like this screenshot below.

    Next, click the "New repository" button. It should redirect you to a new page.

    Then follow the steps from the screenshot below.

    Once the repository is created, click the "<> Code ▿" button (usually, it's coloured green). It should give you a dropdown with a toggle for Local or Codespaces. Click "Codespaces" then click "Create codespace on main". Look at the screenshot below for reference.

    It should take you to a cloud environment using VSCode Web as the interface. Deno is not installed there by default so let's do that in the next step.

    Installing Deno

    ℹ️ This section works for users that use a local MacOS/Linux environment or GitHub Codespaces.

    To install Deno, head to their website https://deno.com and scroll down a bit. You will see an Install Deno section with the commands to install precompiled binaries for Deno.

    Here is a sample command for installing Deno in MacOS/Linux from their website.

    Once you run the command, you will be prompted with "Edit shell configs to add deno to the PATH?". Type "Y" and press Enter.

    You may also want to install shell completions. Press the space bar to select or deselect. Press Enter.

    Be sure to close your current terminal and open a new terminal so the updated environmental variables get loaded.

    You can check that Deno is properly installed by running the following command.

    deno upgrade

    As of writing, Deno's version is 2.1.2.

    🙂 Disclaimer: You are free to install Deno in any fashion like building from source or using your system's package manager. Ensure that the builds work and have a version of at least 2.1.2. However, those methods will not be included in the campaign.

  • Step 2: Preparing Your Project

    Local users have to create a new directory called hono-with-deno. To create one, run the following command.

    mkdir hono-with-deno

    At this point, both local and cloud environment users have the same project directory and should relatively follow the instructions further down ahead. Run the following commands.

    touch deno.json
deno add "jsr:@hono/hono"

    This will create a file called deno.json and install the package Hono from the Javascript Registry (JSR).

    Install the Deno plugin for VSCode.

    Finally, click and hold Ctrl + Shift and press P. You should search for the VSCode command "Deno: Initialize Workspace Configuration". This should help you set up your environment that it's a Deno project. It will create a .vscode directory at the root directory of your project.

    This is preference but you might want to edit the settings.json in the .vscode directory to get the better settings. Replace your settings.json with the following code.

    {
  "biome.enabled": false,
  "deno.enable": true,
  "deno.cacheOnSave": true,
  "deno.lint": true,
  "deno.codeLens.references": true,
  "deno.codeLens.implementations": true,
  "deno.codeLens.referencesAllFunctions": true,
  "deno.codeLens.test": true,
  "deno.codeLens.testArgs": [
	"--allow-all",
	"--no-check"
  ],
  "[typescript]": {
    "editor.defaultFormatter": "denoland.vscode-deno",
    "editor.formatOnSave": true,
  },
}
    JSON

    Your directory structure should look like the screenshot below for VSCode.

    Now that you have everything prepared, let's start learning Hono.

  • Step 3: What is Hono?

    Hono is a web application framework like Express and Oak. But unlike other middleware frameworks, Hono is built around Web Standards, something it takes pride for.

    Because of this, it can be run on different runtimes such as Node, Deno, and Bun. It has abstractions around Web Standards allowing a very fast and easy development experience.

    To start, let's create a new file called main.ts at the root directory of your project.

    import { Hono } from "@hono/hono";
const app = new Hono();

app.get("/", (c) => c.text("Hono!"));

if (import.meta.main) {
  Deno.serve({ hostname: "127.0.0.1", port: 5555 }, app.fetch);
}
    TypeScript

    Save the file. Run the following command on your terminal.

    deno run main.ts

    You will be asked to allow network access. The prompt should look like the screenshot below.

    Type "y" then press Enter. You now have an HTTP server running at hostname "127.0.0.1" on port "5555".

    Next, register an account for free at their website.

    The app looks like this (see screenshot below), it should look similar to your platform as well since it's an Electron app.

  • Step 5: Why Hono is Fast? And Does It Matter?

    Hono is fast because it uses Web Standard Request under the hood which makes it not only performant and fast, but also runtime-agnostic. Therefore, it can run almost anywhere such as Node, Deno and Bun.

    Hono is also fast because of the use of RegExpRouter. Hono has a very good explanation for how it works at this link.

    You can see benchmarks that includes Hono in the following from

    • https://github.com/denosaurs/bench?tab=readme-ov-file#hello-bench; and
    • https://hono.dev/docs/concepts/benchmarks

    However, is being fast really everything 🤔? Benchmarks exist to be used as a point of reference for choosing a framework. Even though there are faster frameworks out there, what developers should look for is something decently fast enough that the benchmarks don't matter. A mere 10k requests per second will only be noticeably slower if compared to something like 80k requests per second. But Hono so far hovers around 50k requests and that's a sweet spot!

    What really matters next is the developer experience 😍

    Hono has first-class Typescript support, runtime-agnostic, and has very clean abstractions around Web Standard APIs which results in a very small size at 14KB if used without plugins.

    But plugins are great! By default, Hono contains built-in middlewares that are commonly used during development. Not only is that great but a batteries-included framework is what most look for 🙏.

  • Step 6: Let's Experiment with Routes

    Now that you have learned a bit about why Hono is fast and why it's runtime-agnostic, let's move towards adding more code to your project!

    For our example, the planned layout is to create an API for microbiological species data that includes details such as genus, species, full name, and habitats.

    Open the file main.ts at the root directory of your project. Replace all of its contents with the following code.

    import { Hono } from "@hono/hono";
import { HTTPException } from "@hono/hono/http-exception";
const app = new Hono().basePath("/api");

interface SpeciesDetails {
  genus: string;
  species: string;
  full_name: string;
  habitats: Array<string>;
}

const MicrobialData: Record<string, SpeciesDetails | undefined> = {
  "helicobacter_pylori": {
    genus: "Helicobacter",
    species: "pylori",
    full_name: "Helicobacter pylori",
    habitats: [
      "aquatic",
      "human gut",
    ],
  },
  "escherichia_coli": {
    genus: "Escherichia",
    species: "coli",
    full_name: "Escherichia coli",
    habitats: [
      "aquatic",
      "human gut",
    ],
  },
};

app.get("/species/:name", (c) => {
  const { name } = c.req.param();
  const data = MicrobialData[name];
  if (data !== undefined) {
    return c.json(data);
  } else {
    throw new HTTPException(404, { message: "Species not found in database." });
  }
}).delete((c) => {
  const { name } = c.req.param();
  const data = MicrobialData[name];
  if (data !== undefined) {
    MicrobialData[name] = undefined;
    return c.text(`Deleted ${name} in database`);
  } else {
    throw new HTTPException(404, { message: "Species not found in database." });
  }
});

app.get("/species/:name/habitats", async (c) => {
  const { name } = c.req.param();
  const data = MicrobialData[name];
  if (data !== undefined) {
    const res = await app.request(`/api/species/${name}`);
    const data: SpeciesDetails | undefined = await res.json();
    if (data) {
      return c.json({ habitats: data.habitats });
    } else {
      throw new HTTPException(503, { message: "Server Error." });
    }
  } else {
    throw new HTTPException(404, { message: "Species not found in database." });
  }
});

if (import.meta.main) {
  Deno.serve({ hostname: "127.0.0.1", port: 5555 }, app.fetch);
}
    TypeScript

    The new code contains a global variable MicrobialData that holds two example species represented as type Record<string, SpeciesDetails | undefined>. The app variable now has a base path of /api. This means that API calls should start with /api and not /.

    There are new routes called /species/:name and /species/:name/habitats. The first one has two existing methods, GET and DELETE. If you are familiar with Express and other middleware frameworks, the syntax with colon and name (:name) are called path parameters. This allows API calls where some paths are considered as parameters for the API calls.

    Run the new code by following this video demo.

    And here is a video demo for those that use GitHub Codespace.

    As shown in the video, Hono supports chained routing that allows one route to have multiple request methods such as GET and DELETE. Here, you already saw it in action with the route http://127.0.0.1:5555/api/species/helicobacter_pylori.

    You can observe that the user performed a GET request to http://127.0.0.1:5555/api/species/helicobacter_pylori. Thus, yours should receive a similar output like in the video. Next, the user performed a DELETE request to http://127.0.0.1:5555/api/species/helicobacter_pylori. This should remove helicobacter_pylori in the record and this is evident that it does not exist any more when trying to perform a GET request to http://127.0.0.1:5555/api/species/helicobacter_pylori again.

    Now, perform a GET request to http://127.0.0.1:5555/api/species/escherichia_coli/habitats. Do you think it makes sense to add a DELETE method for this route? Or do you also think there might be a good reason to add other request methods instead such as PUT?

    Share your thoughts in our Discord channel!

  • Step 7: Stacking It Up!

    At this point, you might notice that running the following command.

    deno run main.ts

    will make you interact with its prompts again and again. To avoid that, open your deno.json file.

    Edit the file to look like the code below.

    {
  "imports": {
    "@hono/hono": "jsr:@hono/hono@^4.6.12"
  },
  "tasks": {
	"serve": "deno run --watch -A main.ts"
  }
}
    JSON

    With this, one can just run the following command to run the HTTP server.

    deno task serve

    With the --watch flag added, this command will rerun the server whenever the watcher detects some file changes. A file change detection will look like this.

    That wraps it all up for Quest 1 of Fuel Up Your API Development with Hono and Deno.
